idCitation.resTitle: The Australian Population Grid derived from 2016 Estimated Residential Population

dataIdInfo.idPurp: A geographic representation of the Australian estimated residential population from 2016
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
The Australian Population Grid is the second population grid to be released by the ABS. It was created using preliminary 2016 Estimated Residential Population (ERP) at SA1 level data. The SA1 level ERP data was then modelled down to a 1km x 1km grid across geographic Australia using various point layers that represent population.

The value of each grid cell represents the population density (number of people per square kilometre) in that 1km x 1km cell. This is modelled data and caution must be used in its interpretation, population has NOT been measured at the 1km cell level.

The SA1 areas used are defined by the 2011 Australian Statistical Geography Standard (ASGS)and the grid used is based on the National Nested Grid Standard.

The Australian Population Grid is part of the ABS Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2015-16 publication (Catalogue no. 3218.0). For further information on this publication please see the Explanatory Notes.

Previous release

The first population grid released by the ABS was derived from the 2011 Australian Population Census using Usual Residential Population data at meshblock level which is also part of the 2011 ASGS (located here).

dataLineage.statement:
Point layers
* GNAF (November 2016) https://www.psma.com.au/ * AGIL 2013 http://data.gov.au/dataset/agil-dataset/ * Locality centroids (November 2016) https://www.psma.com.au/ * Gazetteer 2012 http://www.ga.gov.au/placename * 2011 SA1 centroids http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/Lookup/1270.0.55.001Main+Features1July%202011?OpenDocument
Processing steps
1) A subset of GNAF that represented residential addresses as closely as possible was made, to this was added all the AGIL, Locality and SA1 centroid points. The Gazetteer was also subsetted as to keep residential points. All these layers were combined into a single point layer (Allpoints). 2) The Allpoints layer was overlaid with the 2011 SA1 boundaries to give every point an SA1 code. Points without an SA1 code (outside all SA1 regions) were dropped. 3) Points were prioritised according to their source layer. The GNAF and AGIL points were treated as top priority as per these rules: a) delete all Locality, Gazetteer and SA1 centroid points in SA1 regions that already have GNAF or AGIL points, b) delete all Gazetteer and SA1 centroid points in SA1 regions that have zero GNAF points AND zero AGIL points AND at least one Locality point, c) delete all SA1 centroids in SA1 regions that have zero GNAF points AND zero AGIL points AND zero Locality points but have at least one Gazetteer point. 4) Drop points that are in an SA1 with zero Estimated Residential Population (ERP) and calculate population density. 5) Create the 1km raster layer of population density using the output template.
